There are several options to bring in data into Synapse. These are:
1. Using Synapse pipelines to import data
2. Using Azure Data Factory to import data
3. Using SQL Server Integration Services (SSIS) to import data
4. Using a COPY statement to import data
*/

-- Create a HASH distributed table
CREATE TABLE FactSales (
  SalesID INT IDENTITY(1, 1) NOT NULL, 
  SalesDate DATETIME NOT NULL, 
  SalesItemId INT,
  Description VARCHAR(500)
) WITH ( CLUSTERED INDEX (SalesID), DISTRIBUTION = 
HASH(SalesDate) );

/*
insert into dbo.FactSales (SalesDate, SalesItemId, Description)
values ('2024-03-11 02:10:18.145', 15, 'bought a notepad');
*/

/* 1. uses a hash function to distribute table rows across the available compute nodes
2. this type of distribution is created to minimize data movement across various distributions because similar values tend to fall within the same distribution
3. Tables that are more than 2 Gigabytes (GB) in size on disk and tables having more frequent 
INSERT, UPDATE, and DELETE operations are the best candidates for hash distributions
*/

-- Create a round robin (default distriubtion type in SQL pool)
CREATE TABLE DimSalesItem (
  SalesItemID INT IDENTITY(1, 1) NOT NULL, 
  Description VARCHAR(500)
) WITH ( CLUSTERED INDEX (SalesItemID), DISTRIBUTION = ROUND_ROBIN );

/*
1. default distribution type for a table in SQL Pool is round-robin distribution, whereby 
data is divided evenly across all the distributions
2. Sometimes, rows need to be reshuffled when you perform joining operations on round-robin distributed tables
3. Temporary staging tables and tables with no obvious joining key are the best candidates 
for ROUND_ROBIN distributed tables
*/

-- Create Replicated tables
CREATE TABLE [dbo].[DimSalesRegion] 
(
    RegionID INT IDENTITY(1,1) NOT NULL,
    Region VARCHAR(50) NOT NULL
)
    WITH ( CLUSTERED COLUMNSTORE INDEX, DISTRIBUTION = 
REPLICATE )

/*
1. Replicated tables must only be used for small dimension tables
2. This replicates the table data across all distributions so that the data becomes local to each compute node and 
accessibility becomes easier
3. There is no need to move the data across various compute nodes for a running query, and this 
helps to return results very quickly
4. Small dimension tables with a size less than 2 GB are the best candidates for replicated tables
*/

-- to check data skew for a distributed table
DBCC PDW_SHOWSPACEUSED('dbo.FactSales');

-- an example of using partitions along with distributions
Create table [dbo].[FactSales_new] (
    [SalesID] int NOT NULL,
    [OrderDateKey] int NOT NULL,
    [CustomerKey] int NOT NULL,
    [PromotionKey] int NOT NULL,
    [ProductKey] int NOT NULL,
    [SalesOrderNumber] nvarchar(20) NOT NULL,
    [OrderQuantity] smallint NOT NULL, 
    [UnitPrice] money NOT NULL,
    [SalesAmount] money NOT NULL
) with (
    CLUSTERED COLUMNSTORE INDEX,
    DISTRIBUTION = HASH([ProductKey]),
    PARTITION(
        [OrderDateKey] RANGE RIGHT FOR
        VALUES
        (
            20000101, 20010101, 20020101, 20030101,
            20040101, 20050101
        )
    )
);

SELECT B.distribution_id, A.pdw_node_id, A.[type] AS node_type, A.name AS node_name,
C.partition_number,C.[rows] FROM sys.dm_pdw_nodes A
LEFT JOIN sys.pdw_distributions B ON A.pdw_node_id=B.pdw_node_id
LEFT JOIN sys.pdw_nodes_partitions C ON B.distribution_id=C.
distribution_id AND A.pdw_node_id=C.pdw_node_id
ORDER BY B.distribution_id
GO

-- create temporary tables
IF OBJECT_ID('tempdb..#tempFactSales') IS NOT NULL
BEGIN
    DROP TABLE #tempFactSales
END
GO
CREATE TABLE #tempFactSales
WITH
(
    DISTRIBUTION = HASH([SalesID])
,    HEAP
)
AS
(
SELECT SalesId,SalesItemId, Description
FROM dbo.FactSales
);
SELECT * FROM #tempFactSales
